==== Various bracelets ====
[[File:Dacian Gold Bracelet at the National Museum of Romanian History 2011 - 3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Hinova]]'s gold bracelet, Bronze Age{{sfn|Leahu|2003|p=134}} or early Hallstatt {{sfn|Laszlo|2001|p=350}}]]
Archaeological finds include two gold cylindrical muffs, a characteristic type of the middle and late Bronze Age and widespread throughout Central Europe. Two bronze specimens, both similar to the gold ones, have been discovered at [[Cehal|Cehăluţ]].{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}} The open cuff found at [[Hinova]], and dated to the 12th century BC, is one of the largest gold bracelets of the proto-Dacians found to date. It is made of large gold sheet of 580&nbsp;grams (1.27 pounds) in weight and decorated with ten buttons fixed into holes, five on each end.{{sfn| Hagioglu|Gheorghies|2010|p=117}}{{sfn| Leahu|2003|p=1 poz. 134}}

Bracelets from [[Băleni, Galaţi]] (Late Romanian Bronze Age, Noua Culture) are particularly interesting because of their geometric décor, bands of right or oblique lines. They all have a green patina ranging from dark green to dull green, bluish green, bluish gloss.{{sfn|Vauthey|Vauthey|1968|p=345}}

The fragmentary iron bracelet from the cremation cemetery found at [[Bobda]] is among the few unequivocally dated iron objects equivalent to [[Hallstatt|Hallstatt A 1–2]] in this region.{{sfn| Stoia|1989|p=77}}{{sfn| Pleiner|1982|p=168}}

A bracelet with snake-shape endings had been found at the [[Hallstatt Culture|Hallstattian]] necropolis in [[Ferigile]] ([[Vâlcea County]]).{{sfn| Vulpe | 1967|p=73}}

==== Spălnaca (Hopârta) ====
The bracelets from [[Hopârta|Spălnaca (Hopârta)]] are dated to Bronze Age IV (Iron Age I){{sfn|Coles|Harding|1979|p=409}} and have decorations of geometric characters. Although not directly influenced by the Hallstatt styles, the objects from Spalnaca pre-date the later tendencies for geometric surface decoration of chiseled or engraved lines.{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=12}} Such discoveries at Spalnaca, Guterita and Dipsa show that bronze craftsmanship still flourished in the North Thracians from the Carpathian-Black Sea and Danube areas at the beginning of the Iron Age.{{sfn|Popescu|1971|p=37}}{{sfn|Petrescu-Dâmbovita|1996|p=597}}

==== Multi-spiral types ====
[[File:ThumbTezaurMNIR.JPG|thumb|right|Multi-spirals type gold bracelet from Hinova, Late Bronze Age{{sfn|Leahu|2003|p=136}} or Early Hallstatt{{sfn|Laszlo|2001|p=350}}]]
This type of Dacian bracelet originated in the Bronze Age.{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}} The hoard found in 1980 at [[Hinova]] includes two such bracelets.{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}} Multi-spiral types can be dated to the early Hallstatt periodand comprises also open and closed-end bracelets.{{sfn|Laszlo|2001|p=350}} One of the spiral bracelets from Hinova weighed 261.55&nbsp;grams and the other 497.13&nbsp;grams.{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}} The former, made of a thinner and narrower gold leaf, had a decoration consisting of two furrows cut along the edges and separated by a median crest.{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}} A similar decoration, of a furrow along the median line, decorates a metal bracelet from the deposit found at [[Sânnicolau Român]], dated to the second period of the Bronze Age.{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=93}}

Finds from Dacia include spiral bracelets made of double gold wire, the largest of which weighed nearly a hundred grams. Gold spiral bracelets of this type have been discovered in Transylvania and [[Banat]], spanning a long period which begins with the very late phase of the Bronze Age and ends with the middle Hallstatt. Similar pieces made of bronze were discovered in the deposit of bronze objects at [[Slătioara, Vâlcea|Sacot-Slatioara]].{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=94}}

The multi-spiral bracelet type spans a long period of time that includes all Hallstattian stages.{{sfn|Popa|Berciu|1965|p=63}}

=== Spiral motif ===
[[File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic9 quandrangular and crenelated.jpg|thumb|Quadrangular bracelets ([[Sighetu Marmaţiei]]?) The small ones may have been used as currency.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 212}}]]
The traditional ornamental motifs of bracelets, the meander and the "whirling" spiral (i.e. Oradea, Firiteaz and Sacosul mare), are thought to follow the spread of a cult of the sun, their decorations suggesting the rotation of the sun on the heavenly vault.{{sfn|Dragut |Florea|1984|p=31}} This motif is recognized as one of the parallels between the artifact decorations of this North Thracian group and the ornamentations from the [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]] [[Shaft Graves]]. It is found in both the [[Aegean Islands|Aegean]] and east-central Europe from the Neolithic onwards.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=53}}

Scholars opinions are divided on the source of these comparable traits. One opinion states that the North Thracian spiral motifs originate from the local [[Eneolithic|Eneolithic (Chalcolithic)]] antecedents rather than from any imported influence.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}} There are specific forms widespread in northern Thrace that are unlikely inspired by the Mycenaeans.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}} It is also argued that these motifs apparently did not appear in the intervening territory of South Thrace.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=53}} With North Thracians, the spiral motif appears prominently in the form of massive armguard (armlet) terminals, offering physical as well as [[apotropaic]] protection.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=53}} Hoddinott states that the twin spiral terminals, as on the bowl from [[Şona|Biia]], would have been a natural development; either from a local single armlet type or from an [[Unetice culture|Unetice]] spectacle pendant.{{sfn| Hoddinott |1989|p=53}}

The other opinion attributes the spiral motif to a northward spread of Mycenaean influence.{{sfn|Dumitrescu|1972|p=258}} It is argued that the spiral of the Neolithic period disappeared during the transitional period towards the Bronze Age, and even during the Early Bronze Age; therefore, starting from the Middle Bronze Age the spiral would occur because of a Mycenaean sway to the north of the Danube.{{sfn|Dumitrescu|1972|p=258}} These comparable features might have occurred because of commercial relations between the Mycenaeans and Dacians relating to the gold mines of Transylvania.{{sfn|Samsaris|1989|p=169}}

==== Spiral ending types ====
===== Sacoşu Mare =====
Whatever may have been the origin of the spiral motif, the craftsmen of the late [[Bronze Age|Carpatho-Danubian Bronze Age IV]] and [[Hallstatt|Hallstatt A]] had a marked preference for bracelets with a spiral ending, as found at [[Sacosu Mare]].{{sfn| MacKenzie|1986|p=94}} The same décor featuring the coiled disk endings of the single- or double-spiral bracelets is found on contemporary ceramics.{{sfn|Burda|1979|p=17}} There is also a striking resemblance between the gold bracelets from Sacoșu Mare, from [[Şagu|Firighiaz (or Firiteaz)]], and from other locations in Transylvania that suggest a spiritual affinity in the proto-Dacian world.{{sfn|Burda|1979|p=17}}

The hoard from Sacoşu Mare consists of bracelets and jewelry dated to the 13th to 12th centuries BC (Late Bronze Age and Hallstatt I).{{sfn| Leahu|2004|p=1}} The golden bracelets, around 74.15&nbsp;grams (2.6 ounces), have open ends of approximately 6.6&nbsp;cm (2.6&nbsp;inches) in diameter. Some terminate with convex volute ends,{{sfn| Leahu|2004|p=1}} while others have double convex volute ends.{{sfn| Leahu|2011|p=1}} The bracelet's bar is decorated with engraved rows of diamonds flanked by dotted lines.{{sfn| Leahu|2011|p=1}}

