{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Fernand Léger, 1922, Still Life with Candlestick, oil on canvas, 116 x 80 cm, Musée d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris.jpg | image_size= | title= Still Life with Candlestick | other_language_1=French | other_title_1= Nature morte aux chandeliers | artist=[[Fernand Léger]] | year=1922 | medium=Oil on canvas | height_metric=116 | width_metric=80 | height_imperial=45.6 | width_imperial=31.5 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city= | museum=Stolen from [[Musée d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris]] in 2010 }}
'''''Still Life with Candlestick''''' (French: '''''Nature morte aux chandeliers''''', '''''Nature morte, chandeliers''''', '''''Nature morte au chandelier''''', '''''Le chandelier''''') is an oil painting created in 1922 by the French artist [[Fernand Léger]].
This painting was stolen to order on 20 May 2010 from the [[Musée d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris]]. The museum reported the overnight theft of five paintings from its collection, valued at {{Nowrap|€100 million}} (&nbsp;{{Nowrap|$123 million USD}}), though this may be conservative.<ref>[https://www.tate.org.uk/context-comment/articles/gallery-lost-art-theft-of-five-paintings Jennifer Mundy, ''Lost Art: Theft of Five Paintings'', Tate], 22 October 2012</ref><ref name="sky">{{cite news|last=Hewage |first=Tim |title=Thief Steals Paintings In Paris Art Heist |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Thief-Steals-Paintings-In-Paris-Art-Heist-Valued-at-Five-Million-Euros-From-Modern-Art-Museum/Article/201005315635454?lpos=World_News_First_World_News_Article_Teaser_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15635454_Thief_Steals_Paintings_In_Paris_Art_Heist_Valued_at_Five_Million_Euros_From_Modern_Art_Museum |accessdate=20 May 2010 |newspaper=Sky News |date=20 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826021142/http://news.sky.com:80/skynews/Home/World-News/Thief-Steals-Paintings-In-Paris-Art-Heist-Valued-at-Five-Million-Euros-From-Modern-Art-Museum/Article/201005315635454?lpos=World_News_First_World_News_Article_Teaser_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15635454_Thief_Steals_Paintings_In_Paris_Art_Heist_Valued_at_Five_Million_Euros_From_Modern_Art_Museum |archivedate=26 August 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Guardian">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Sam|title=Picasso and Matisse masterpieces stolen from Paris museum|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/may/20/picasso-matisse-stolen-paris-museum|accessdate=20 May 2010|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 May 2010}}</ref>
The principle suspect, Vjeran Tomic (nicknamed "Spider-Man" for his ability to scale buildings),<ref>[https://news.artnet.com/art-world/107-million-spider-man-heist-art-thrown-out-840893 Sarah Cascone, ''Defendant Claims He Threw Out Modern and Impressionist Masterpieces After ‘Spider-Man’ Heist''], Artnet News, 31 January 2017</ref> was commissioned by antiques dealer Jean-Michel Corvez to steal this painting by Léger. In the process, he stole paintings by Picasso, Matisse, Modigliani, and Braque.<ref name="Fincham">[http://illicitculturalproperty.com/five-paintings-stolen-from-the-museum-of-modern-art-in-paris-feared-destroyed/ Derek Fincham, ''Five paintings stolen from the Museum of Modern Art in Paris feared destroyed''], 1 February 2017</ref><ref name="theguardian">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/31/paris-art-theft-spider-man-trial-picasso-matisse-thrown-away ''I threw away $100m of Picasso and Matisse art, says dealer in Paris theft trial''], Associated Press, theguardian.com, 30 January 2017</ref>
The paintings taken, in addition to ''Still Life with Chandeliers'', were ''[[Le pigeon aux petits pois]]'' (''Dove with Green Peas'', or ''Pigeon with Peas'', 1911) by [[Pablo Picasso]], ''[[La Pastorale (Henri Matisse)|La Pastorale]]'' (1906) by [[Henri Matisse]], ''[[L'Olivier Près de l'Estaque]]'' (''Olive Tree near [[L'Estaque]]'', 1906) by [[Georges Braque]], ''{{Interlanguage link multi|La Femme à l'Éventail|fr|3=La Femme à l'éventail (Modigliani)}}'' (''Woman with a Fan'', 1919) by [[Amedeo Modigliani]].<ref name="sky">{{cite news|last=Hewage |first=Tim |title=Thief Steals Paintings In Paris Art Heist |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/World-News/Thief-Steals-Paintings-In-Paris-Art-Heist-Valued-at-Five-Million-Euros-From-Modern-Art-Museum/Article/201005315635454?lpos=World_News_First_World_News_Article_Teaser_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15635454_Thief_Steals_Paintings_In_Paris_Art_Heist_Valued_at_Five_Million_Euros_From_Modern_Art_Museum |accessdate=20 May 2010 |newspaper=Sky News |date=20 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826021142/http://news.sky.com:80/skynews/Home/World-News/Thief-Steals-Paintings-In-Paris-Art-Heist-Valued-at-Five-Million-Euros-From-Modern-Art-Museum/Article/201005315635454?lpos=World_News_First_World_News_Article_Teaser_Region_0&lid=ARTICLE_15635454_Thief_Steals_Paintings_In_Paris_Art_Heist_Valued_at_Five_Million_Euros_From_Modern_Art_Museum |archivedate=26 August 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref name="Guardian">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Sam|title=Picasso and Matisse masterpieces stolen from Paris museum|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/may/20/picasso-matisse-stolen-paris-museum|accessdate=20 May 2010|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 May 2010}}</ref> A window had been smashed and CCTV footage showed a masked man taking the paintings.<ref name="sky"/> Authorities believe the thief acted alone.<ref name=France24>{{cite news|title=Matisse, Picasso and other masterpieces stolen from Paris museum |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20100520-matisse-picasso-other-masterpieces-art-stolen-paris-museum-heist-france|accessdate=20 May 2010|newspaper=[[France 24]]|date=20 May 2010}}</ref> The man carefully removed the paintings from their frames, which he left behind.<ref name="times">{{cite news|last=Bremner|first=Charles|title=Masked thief steals masterpieces worth €500 million from Paris museum|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article7131750.ece|accessdate=20 May 2010|newspaper=The Times|date=20 May 2010}}</ref>
The theft, executed with an extreme level of sophistication,<ref>[https://france-amerique.com/en/vol-de-cinq-tableaux-dont-un-picasso-et-un-matisse-dans-un-musee-a-paris/ ''Vol de cinq tableaux, dont un Picasso et un Matisse, dans un musée à Paris''], France-Amérique, 20 May 2010</ref> is being investigated by the [[Brigade de Répression du Banditisme]] specialist unit of the French Police.<ref name="Guardian"/> It is unclear why the alarm systems in the museum failed to detect the robbery. Staff only noticing when they arrived at the museum just before {{Nowrap|7:00 am}}.<ref name="Guardian"/><ref name="BBC">{{cite news|title=Five masterpieces stolen from Paris modern art museum|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/10130840.stm|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=20 May 2010|date=20 May 2010}}</ref> The museum closed on 20 May 2010, citing "technical reasons".<ref name="times"/> The theft follows the [[Art theft#Emile B.C3.BChrle Foundation in Zurich .282008.29|$162 million heist]] of masterpieces by [[Cézanne]], [[Degas]], [[Van Gogh]] and [[Monet]] from [[Foundation E.G. Bührle]] in [[Zurich]] in February 2008 and could be one of the biggest art thefts in history (by value). It has been described as the "heist of the century".<ref name=France24/><ref name="hindu">{{cite news|title=Thieves steal works by Picasso, others in Paris|url=http://beta.thehindu.com/news/international/article434377.ece|accessdate=20 May 2010|newspaper=The Hindu|date=20 May 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130104230657/http://beta.thehindu.com/news/international/article434377.ece|archivedate=4 January 2013|df=}} </ref><ref name="LES">{{cite news|title=£430 million art stolen from Paris museum in 'heist of the century' |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23836258-pound-430-million-art-stolen-from-paris-museum-in-heist-of-the-century.do |accessdate=20 May 2010 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=20 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522061925/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk:80/standard/article-23836258-pound-430-million-art-stolen-from-paris-museum-in-heist-of-the-century.do |archivedate=22 May 2010 |df= }}</ref> The French auctioneer and president of the {{ill|Association du Palais de Tokyo|fr|Palais de Tokyo}}, {{ill|Pierre Cornette de Saint-Cyr|fr}}, commented, "These five paintings are unsellable, so thieves, sirs, you are imbeciles, now return them."
The thief and his sponsor were found one year after the heist, and the latter declared that he was seized by panic after a police raid and a phone call by the police. For fear that investigators were closing in, accomplices apparently destroyed the paintings.<ref name="Fincham" /> "I threw them into the trash," cried Yonathan Birn, one of three people on trial in the case, "I made the worst mistake of my existence." However, neither the judge or other defendants believe Birn is telling the truth. Authorities believe all of the paintings were removed from France. Birn's co-defendants testified he was "too smart" to destroy €100 million worth of artwork.<ref name="theguardian" />
